      <title>Why I Hate Windows Defender</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/bad-windows-defender/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 11 Jul 2022 11:36:33 -0500</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/bad-windows-defender/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Windows Defender is often seen as a good antivirus, but I want to inform you of a cost noone sees but developers because of Defender.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;is-windows-defender-good&#34;&gt;Is Windows Defender Good?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Yes. It does detect a ton of viruses and have good detection rates as long as you are online, since it relies heavily on its online connection. However, there is a dark side to having Microsoft control this entire part of your PC that we need to go over. The false positives are excessive and I believe it is by design.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-mafia-for-software-developers&#34;&gt;The Mafia for Software Developers&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/images/2022-thumbs/bad-windows-defender.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;bad-defender&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Smartscreen is powered by Windows Defender and you have to buy a $300 A YEAR code signing license with Extended Validation to bypass it. The EV cert is close to the mafia extorting business users for &amp;ldquo;protection&amp;rdquo;. If you don&amp;rsquo;t use Defender, you don&amp;rsquo;t need to worry about smartscreen. Using standard code signing with an external anti-virus will work close to the same as Defender is disabled when you use a 3rd party av.&lt;/p&gt;
